      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is dollar cost averaging?</h3>
        <p>Dollar cost averaging (DCA) is an investment strategy where you divide your total investment amount into equal periodic purchases over time, regardless of price. For example, instead of investing $12,000 at once, you invest $1,000 per month for 12 months. This reduces the risk of investing everything at a market peak.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Does dollar cost averaging beat lump sum investing?</h3>
        <p>Historically, lump sum investing outperforms DCA about 68% of the time because markets tend to rise over time. However, DCA reduces downside risk and volatility exposure. DCA is psychologically easier and can be the better choice if you would otherwise avoid investing due to fear of a market drop.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How does a DCA calculator work?</h3>
        <p>A DCA calculator simulates buying a fixed dollar amount of an asset at regular intervals over a set period. It generates a price path based on starting price, ending price, and volatility, then calculates the average cost per share, total shares purchased, and ending portfolio value compared to a lump sum investment.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the best interval for dollar cost averaging?</h3>
        <p>Monthly intervals are the most common and practical for DCA. Weekly or biweekly purchases can slightly reduce timing risk, but the marginal benefit is small. The key factor is consistency — pick an interval that aligns with your income schedule and stick with it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is DCA good for Bitcoin and crypto?</h3>
        <p>DCA is particularly popular for volatile assets like Bitcoin and cryptocurrency. Because crypto prices can swing 50% or more in a short period, DCA smooths out the entry price and reduces the risk of buying at an all-time high. Many crypto investors use automated DCA services for this reason.</p>
      </div>
